This is a dataset of 6497 rows of 12 variables making up the columns. All of the predictor variables are in numeric form aside from the density which is on a scale of 1,2,and 3 meaning low density, medium density, and high density. The response variable is the label which is either good or bad wine. Here is the full list of the variaables and their descriptions: 
fix.acid: fixed acidity (in grams of tartaric acid per decimeter cubed)
vol.acid: volatile acidity (in grams of tartaric acid per decimeter cubed)
citric: citric acid (in grams per decimeter cubed)
sugar: residual sugar (in grams per decimeter cubed)
chlorides: chlorides (in grams of sodium chloride per decimeter cubed)
free.sd: free sulfur dioxide (milligrams per decimeter cubed)
total.sd: total sulfur dioxide (milligrams per decimeter cubed)
density: 1 (= <0.99 g/dm3), 2 (= [0.99,1] g/dm3), or 3 (= >1 g/dm3)
pH: wine acidity
sulphates: grams of potassium sulphate per decimeter cubed
alcohol: percentage of the volume

I tranformed some highly skewed predictor variables logarithmically, attempting to better normalize the variable. I transformed fix.acid, sulphates, alcohol, and vol.acid.  
find_extreme_outliers <- function(x, threshold = 5) {
  if (is.numeric(x)) {
    z_scores <- scale(x)
    return(abs(z_scores) > threshold)
  } else {
    return(rep(FALSE, length(x)))
  }
}

outlier_matrix <- df %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~find_extreme_outliers(.))) %>%
  select(where(is.logical)) %>%
  as.matrix()

rows_without_outliers <- !rowSums(outlier_matrix, na.rm = TRUE)

df_cleaned <- df[rows_without_outliers, ]

set.seed(123)
s <- sample(nrow(df_cleaned),round(0.7*nrow(df_cleaned)))

df.test <- df_cleaned[-s,]
I split the data into a 70-30 split, meaning 70% of the data will be used for training the model and 30% of the data will be used for testing the model.

suppressMessages(library(rpart))
suppressMessages(library(rpart.plot))

rpart.out <- rpart(label ~ ., data = df.train)

prob.pred <- predict(rpart.out, newdata = df.test, type = "prob")[, "GOOD"]

roc.rp <- suppressMessages(roc(df.test$label, prob.pred))
auc_value <- auc(roc.rp)

J <- roc.rp$sensitivities + roc.rp$specificities - 1
w <- which.max(J)
threshold <- roc.rp$thresholds[w]

resp.pred <- ifelse(prob.pred > threshold, "GOOD", "BAD")

rpart.mcr <- mean(resp.pred != df.test$label)

conf_matrix <- table(resp.pred, df.test$label)

cat("Misclassification Rate:", round(rpart.mcr, 3), "\n")
## Misclassification Rate: 0.267
print(conf_matrix)
##          
## resp.pred BAD GOOD
##      BAD  449  264
##      GOOD 253  967
cat("AUC:", round(auc_value, 3), "\n")
## AUC: 0.739
cat("Optimal threshold:", round(threshold, 3), "\n")
## Optimal threshold: 0.659
plot(roc.rp, main = "ROC Curve for rpart model")
points(roc.rp$specificities[w], roc.rp$sensitivities[w], col = "red", pch = 19)
text(roc.rp$specificities[w], roc.rp$sensitivities[w], labels = "Optimal", pos = 4, col = "red")

rpart.plot(rpart.out, extra = 104)

suppressMessages(library(xgboost))

data_train_matrix <- as.matrix(df.train[, !names(df.train) %in% c("label")])
data_test_matrix <- as.matrix(df.test[, !names(df.test) %in% c("label")])

train_labels <- as.numeric(df.train$label == "GOOD")
test_labels <- as.numeric(df.test$label == "GOOD")

train <- xgb.DMatrix(data = data_train_matrix, label = train_labels)
test <- xgb.DMatrix(data = data_test_matrix, label = test_labels)

set.seed(123)

params <- list(
  objective = "binary:logistic",
  eval_metric = "logloss"
)

xgb.cv.out <- xgb.cv(
  params = params,
  data = train,
  nrounds = 30,
  nfold = 5,
  verbose = 0
)

cat("The optimal number of trees is ", which.min(xgb.cv.out$evaluation_log$test_logloss_mean), "\n")
## The optimal number of trees is  27
xgb.out <- xgboost(data = train,
                   nrounds = which.min(xgb.cv.out$evaluation_log$test_logloss_mean),
                   params = list(objective = "binary:logistic"),
                   verbose = 0)

resp.prob <- predict(xgb.out, newdata = test)

roc.xg <- suppressMessages(roc(test_labels, resp.prob))

J <- roc.xg$sensitivities + roc.xg$specificities - 1
w <- which.max(J)
threshold <- roc.xg$thresholds[w]

resp.pred <- ifelse(resp.prob > threshold, 1, 0)

plot(roc.xg, col="red", xlim=c(1,0), ylim=c(0,1))

cat("AUC for xgboost: ", roc.xg$auc, "\n")
## AUC for xgboost:  0.8508584
mcr <- mean(resp.pred != test_labels)
cat("Misclassification Rate:", round(mcr, 3), "\n")
## Misclassification Rate: 0.219
conf_matrix <- table(Predicted = resp.pred, Actual = test_labels)
print(conf_matrix)
##          Actual
## Predicted   0   1
##         0 535 257
##         1 167 974
Above is the xgboost model, which returned the second best MCR and the second best AUC.

suppressMessages(library(FNN))

k.max <- 30
mcr.k <- rep(NA,k.max)
for ( kk in 1:k.max ) {
  knn.out <- knn.cv(train=df.train[,1:11],cl=df.train[,12],k=kk,algorithm="brute")
  mcr.k[kk] <- mean(knn.out!=df.train$label)
}
k.min <- which.min(mcr.k)
cat("The optimal number of nearest neighbors is ",k.min,"\n")
## The optimal number of nearest neighbors is  1
suppressMessages(library(class))
suppressMessages(library(ggplot2))

ggplot(data = data.frame("k" = 1:k.max, "mcr" = mcr.k), mapping = aes(x = k, y = mcr)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_line() +
  xlab("Number of Nearest Neighbors k") + ylab("Validation MCR") + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = k.min, color = "red")

knn.out <- knn(train = df.train[, 1:11], test = df.test[, 1:11], cl = df.train[, 12], k = k.min, prob = TRUE)

knn.prob <- attributes(knn.out)$prob
knn.prob <- ifelse(knn.out == levels(knn.out)[1], 1 - knn.prob, knn.prob)

roc.knn <- roc(df.test$label, knn.prob)
## Setting levels: control = BAD, case = GOOD
## Setting direction: controls < cases
J <- roc.knn$sensitivities + roc.knn$specificities - 1
w <- which.max(J)
threshold <- roc.knn$thresholds[w]

knn.pred <- ifelse(knn.prob > threshold, "GOOD", "BAD")

knn.mcr <- mean(knn.pred != df.test$label)

conf_matrix <- table(knn.pred, df.test$label)

cat("Misclassification Rate:", round(knn.mcr, 3), "\n")
